{"title_page": "Battle of Santiago (1844)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Military Conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Santiago\n| partof      = the [[Dominican War of Independence]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 30 March 1844\n| place       = [[Santiago de los Caballeros]], [[Santiago Province, Dominican Republic|Santiago Province]]\n| result      = Dominican victory\n| combatant1  = [[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Dominican Republic]]\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} [[Haiti]]\n| commander1  = [[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] Gen. [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Imbert]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] Col. [[Pedro Eugenio Pelletier]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[:es:Fernando Valerio|Fernando Valerio]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[:es:Gaspar Polanco|Gaspar Polanco]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} Gen. [[Jean-Louis Pierrot]] <br/> {{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} Gen. St.-Louis\n| strength1   = 400 regulars<br>100 cavalry<br>3 cannons\n| strength2   = 10,000\n| casualties1 = 1 wounded<ref>{{cite book |last1=Calhoun |first1=John Caldwell |last2=Wilson |first2=Clyde Norman |title=The Papers of John C. Calhoun, Volume 21 |date=1959 |publisher=Univ of South Carolina Press |page=61}}</ref>\n| casualties2 = 600\u2013715 killed\n| campaignbox = {{campaignbox Dominican War of Independence}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Santiago''' was the second major battle of the [[Dominican War of Independence]] and was fought on the 30 March 1844, at [[Santiago de los Caballeros]], [[Santiago Province, Dominican Republic|Santiago Province]]. Although outnumbered, Dominican troops, part of the Army of The North and led by General Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Imbert, defeated Haitian Army troops led by General [[Jean-Louis Pierrot]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Authors|first1=Multiple|title=Imperial Wars 1815\u20131914|date=2013|publisher=Amber Books Ltd|isbn=9781782741251|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvKxAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT133&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last1=Authors|first1=Multiple|title=Imperial Wars 1815\u20131914|date=2013|publisher=Amber Books Ltd|isbn=9781782741251|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvKxAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT133&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle of Cabeza de Las Mar\u00edas]] \n* [[Battle of Azua]] \n* [[Battle of El Memiso]] \n* [[Battle of Tortuguero]] \n* [[Battle of Estrelleta]] \n* [[Battle of Beler]] \n* [[Battle of El N\u00famero]] \n* [[Battle of Las Carreras]] \n\n{{coord missing|Dominican Republic}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1844|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Haiti|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Dominican War of Independence|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:1844 in the Dominican Republic]]\n\n\n{{battle-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Santiago\n|partof=the [[Dominican War of Independence]]\n|image=\n|caption=\n|date=30 March 1844\n|place=[[Santiago de los Caballeros]], [[Santiago Province, Dominican Republic|Santiago Province]]\n|result=Dominican victory \n|combatant1=[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Dominican Republic]]\n|combatant2={{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} [[Haiti]]\n|commander1=[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] Gen. [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Imbert]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] Col. [[Pedro Eugenio Pelletier]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[:es:Fernando Valerio|Fernando Valerio]] <br/>[[Image:Flag of the Dominican Republic (up to 1844).svg|border|22px]] [[:es:Gaspar Polanco|Gaspar Polanco]]\n|commander2={{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} Gen. [[Jean-Louis Pierrot]] <br/> {{flagicon|Haiti|civil}} Gen. St.-Louis\n|strength1=400 regulars<br>100 cavalry<br>3 cannons\n|strength2=10,000\n|casualties1=unknown\n|casualties2=600\u2013715 killed\n|campaignbox ={{campaignbox Dominican War of Independence}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Santiago''' was the second major battle of the [[Dominican War of Independence]] and was fought on the 30 March 1844, at [[Santiago de los Caballeros]], [[Santiago Province, Dominican Republic|Santiago Province]]. Although outnumbered, Dominican troops, part of the Army of The North and led by General Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Imbert, defeated Haitian Army troops led by General [[Jean-Louis Pierrot]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Authors|first1=Multiple|title=Imperial Wars 1815\u20131914|date=2013|publisher=Amber Books Ltd|isbn=9781782741251|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvKxAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT133&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last1=Authors|first1=Multiple|title=Imperial Wars 1815\u20131914|date=2013|publisher=Amber Books Ltd|isbn=9781782741251|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvKxAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT133&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle of Cabeza de Las Mar\u00edas]] \n* [[Battle of Azua]] \n* [[Battle of El Memiso]] \n* [[Battle of Tortuguero]] \n* [[Battle of Estrelleta]] \n* [[Battle of Beler]] \n* [[Battle of El N\u00famero]] \n* [[Battle of Las Carreras]] \n\n{{coord missing|Dominican Republic}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1844|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Haiti|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Dominican War of Independence|Santiago 1844]]\n[[Category:1844 in the Dominican Republic]]\n\n\n{{battle-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BabsEverAfter", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Santiago_(1844)"}
{"title_page": "Paquisha War", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Paquisha War\n| partof            = the [[History of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute|Ecuadorian-Peruvian conflicts]]\n| image             = Ecuador-Peru-Frontera.svg\n| image_size        = 280\n| caption           = Ecuador\u2013Peru border\n| date              = {{start and end dates|1981|01|22|1981|02|05|df=y}}\n| place             = Condor mountain range\n| result            = Peruvian Victory <ref>{{cite web|title=Conflicto del Alto Comaina, Ecured Cuba|url=https://www.ecured.cu/Conflicto_del_Alto_Comaina|accessdate=18 February 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018False Paquisha\u2019: 37 years after a military feat, Expreso Diary|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/actualidad/falso-paquisha-a-37-anos-de-una-proeza-militar/|accessdate=29 January 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The other victory: How we achieve peace with Ecuador|url=https://revistaideele.com/ideele/content/la-otra-victoria-c%C3%B3mo-logramos-la-paz-con-el-ecuador|accessdate=7 March 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><br/>The posts installed by the Ecuadorians came to be controlled by the Peruvian Army<ref>{{cite web|title=Paquisha War|url=https://military.wikia.org/wiki/Paquisha_War|accessdate=23 February 2017|language=English}}</ref>\n| combatant1        = {{flag|Peru}}\n| combatant2        = {{flag|Ecuador}}\n| commander1        = {{ubl|[[Fernando Bela\u00fande Terry]]|[[Rafael Hoyos Rubio]]}}\n| commander2        = [[Jaime Rold\u00f3s Aguilera]]\n| strength1         = unknown\n| strength2         = 53 men<ref>{{cite web|title=Paquisha, 35 a\u00f1os de este importante nombre en la historia del Ecuador|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/noticias/2016/01/21/nota/5359180/paquisha-nombre-historia-ecuador|accessdate=8 January 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| casualties1       = 17 killed\n| casualties2       = {{ubl|16 killed|30 wounded}}\n| campaignbox       = {{Campaignbox Ecuadorian-Peruvian}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Paquisha War''' ({{Lang-es|guerra de Paquisha}}) was a military clash that took place between January and February 1981 between [[Ecuador]] and [[Peru]] over the control of three watchposts. While Peru felt that the matter was already decided in the [[Ecuadorian-Peruvian War]] of 1941, Ecuador did not agree with the [[Rio de Janeiro Protocol]]. Later in 1998 the Guarantors of the Rio Protocol ruled that the border of the undelimited zone was indeed the line of the Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor, as Peru had been claiming since the 1940s. \n\nIn the aftermath of the incident, both sides increased their military presence along the [[Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor]] area and Cenepa Valley, starting an escalating spiral of tension and provocation that finally resulted in another military confrontation in 1995, the [[Cenepa War]].\n\nWhile the name ''Paquisha War'' is widely used by the international community and Ecuador, in Spanish this incident is also known as the '''Falso Paquisha War''' (''Conflicto del Falso Paquisha'') in Peru and, occasionally, as the '''Paquisha Incident''' or the '''Upper Comaina Conflict''' (''conflicto del Alto Comaina'').\n\n==Historical background==\n''For details on the history of the border dispute between Ecuador and Peru, please see [[History of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute]].''\n\n===The Paquisha or \"Fake Paquisha\" Incident===\nThe dispute revolved around the existence of three Ecuadorian military outposts, called Paquisha, Mayaico, and Machinaza, located in the valley of the Comaina River, beyond the eastern slopes of the [[Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor|Condor range]] (in Spanish, ''Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor''). While these posts were located in the as yet non-demarcated zone of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian border, the establishment of these posts was considered by the Peruvian Government as a violation of a ''[[status quo]]'' line arranged between the military leaders of both countries in the course of several meetings at the end of the 1970s. During these agreements both sides would have agreed not to establish any new military posts in the disputed areas,<ref>Mena, 1981</ref> which would have meant for Ecuador not to establish any military presence to the east of the ridgeline of the Condor Range.\n\nThe Ecuadorian possession of these posts was denounced by Peruvian representatives at the foreign ministers' meeting of the [[Organization of American States|OAS]], on February 2, 1981. During this meeting, the Peruvian Foreign Minister, [[Javier Arias Stella]], called the three Ecuadorian military outposts ''falsos'' (\"fakes\"), despite Ecuadorian sovereignty.\n\nEcuadorians indicated that these detachments corresponded to the \"Paquisha\" base established in Ecuadorian territory. But, after measuring the coordinates, it was found that they did not correspond to the aforementioned Paquisha accepted in the [[Rio Protocol|Protocol of Rio de Janeiro]] but, as the Peruvian president [[Fernando Bela\u00fande Terry|Fernando Bela\u00fande]] described it, to a \"False Paquisha\", a name he gave to distinguish it easily from the first Paquisha that was legal according to the Rio protocol of 1942<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306200426/https://www.mindef.gob.pe/vercontenido.php?archivo=menu%2Fhistoricos%2Fefem-nacional%2Fefeme-enero3.htm&retorno=si|title=Operations of the False Paquisha|last=|first=|website=Ministry of Defense of Peru|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nThe Ecuadorian Foreign Minister, [[Alfonso Barrera Valderde]], responded to this allegation stating that when Ecuador responded to the attacks on January 22, it always specified that the attacks were being made against the ''destacamentos'' (military outposts) of Paquisha, Mayaicu, and Machinaza, not against the similarly named Ecuadorian towns.<ref>Mena Villamar, Claudio. ''Paquisha: toda la verdad''. Letranueva. Quito, 1981.</ref>\n\nThe [[Peru]] prepared a contingent to recover the post, formed mainly by [[Mil Mi-8|Mi-8TV]] transport helicopters of the Army Aviation and Air Group No. 3, formed by [[Peruvian Air Force|FAP]] A-37, [[Sukhoi Su-17|Su-22]] and [[Dassault Mirage 5|Mirage 5]] aircraft to support to the Jungle Infantry<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caretas.pe/sociedad/%c2%91yo-sobrevivi-al-condor%c2%92/|title=I survived the Condor|last=|first=|date=|website=Magazine Caretas|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nThe [[Peruvian Air Force|Fuerza A\u00e9rea del Peru (FAP)]] flew many sorties with [[Cessna T-37#A-37B|A-37B]], [[Dassault Mirage III|Mirage 5P]] and [[Su-22]] to support these operations. The FAE flew 179 combat missions with [[A-37 Dragonfly|A-37B]] and [[Mirage F-1]] aircraft to counter the FAP attacks. On January 28, 1981 there was a dogfight between 2 A-37Bs of the FAE and FAP.\n\nOn January 30, 1981, [[Peruvian Army|Peruvian troops]] recover the \"PV-22\" (False Paquisha), the next day they recover the \"PV-3\", and on February 1, 1981, they recover the \"PV-4\" (New ) or \"false Mayaico\".\n\nBy that day, the conflict was apparently over but then Peruvians discovered that more troops from Ecuador had settled in 3 other military posts and 3 points on the northeastern border of the Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor and were the \"PV El Mirador\" posts, \"PV-4-A\" and \"PV-4-B\" (Old).\n\nOn February 19, 1981, Peruvians recovered the \"PV Jim\u00e9nez Banda 2\" (False Machinaza) and the next day, on February 20, 1981, the \"PV-4-A\" and \"PV-4-B\" (Old ).\n\nOn February 21, 1981, the [[Peruvian Air Force|Aviation of the Peruvian Army]] destroyed the last military installations of the [[Ecuadorian Army|Army of Ecuador]] that were still in the Peruvian territory.\n\nThe Peruvian operation was a success, the outpost of ''Falso Paquisha'', that was occupied by the Ecuadorians, was taken on February 5, 1981 by Peruvian troops. The conflict, which occurred in a then non-demarcated area of the common border between Ecuador and Peru, ceased with the Ecuadorians being expelled from the slopes and driven back to the summit of the ''Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor''.\n\nThe [[Organization of American States]] (OAS), had to intervene through the Sorrosa-Du Bois Act, setting the location coordinates allowed for border troops, ratifying the condition of the mentioned mountain range as a natural boundary between the two countries.\n\nAccording to a Peruvian journalistic information, which shows a photo that shows the capture of a powerful machine gun multiple guns with 4 guns of 50 mm. of caliber in \u201cFalse Paquisha\u201d, the installation of this type of armament represented the symbol of the gravity of the premeditated Ecuadorian invasion in Peruvian territory, through the Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tierra-inca.com/album/photos/view.php?dep=1&id=2364|title=Conflict with Ecuador, False Paquisha|last=|first=|date=|website=Inca Land|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. According to specialists, only a detachment of high strategic value justifies the installation of an artillery piece of these characteristics. Known versions after the eviction of the Ecuadorian troops, between January 28 and February 1, 1981, confirm that this frustrated occupation was planned since 1977, when the first clashes between border patrols began to occur. Another second machine gun of the same characteristics would be captured by Peruvian soldiers in the \"False Machinaza\" Post (named by the Peruvians \"Jim\u00e9nez Banda 2\") which was another of the positions invaded by Ecuadorians<ref>{{Cite book|title=XXV Anniversary of Military Operations in the Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor (1981-2006).|last=Moncada Novoa|first=Ricardo|publisher=Permanent Commission of History of the Army of Peru.|year=December 2005|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>.\n\nAs a result, the Peruvian and Ecuadorian governments, with assistance of each one of the Guarantors, agreed to separate their forces. This \"[[gentleman's agreement]]\" remained in effect throughout the 1980s, with various measures taken to codify conduct of patrols encountering one another in the disputed area.\n\nThe meeting concluded with a resolution that announced a cease fire in the conflict zone, and noted that both countries had accepted a commission of representatives from the [[guarantor]]  countries to safeguard the observance of the cease fire and establish conditions for peace between Peru and Ecuador.<ref>[http://ecuador.nativeweb.org/border/border1.html ''ecuador.nativeweb.org'']</ref>\n\n===Context of the \"gentlemen's agreement.\"===\n\nTo avoid the disaster of 1941 in regard to loss of civilian lives and a possible invasion to the south of Ecuador, the High Command sent twenty-five thousand men under the command of General [[Richelieu Levoyer]] with the task of defending possible invasion pathways.\n\nUntil then the Ecuadorian Defense Plan envisaged a logistics operations taking about eight days to set up defensive positions. Levoyer proposed a new plan which placed all personnel, weapons, supplies, etc., in twenty-four hours in the front and ready to fulfill the mission of defense.\n\nThe Peruvian armed forces were surprised by the rapid deployment of Ecuadorian forces, so, thinking that Levoyer and his men might invade the north of Peru, they organized anti-tank defense lines, trenches, and other defenses.\n\nFortunately, events did not lead to general war. The widespread confrontation was avoided probably because of the direct talks between top military Commanders of the two countries, and the military Delegates of Chile, Argentina, Brazil and USA. The talks took place in the border line near the Pacific Ocean, in the towns of Huaquillas (Ecuador, Province of El Oro) and Aguas Verdes (Peru, Department of Tumbes). The result was the Sorrosa-Du Bois Act.\n\nThe cycle of direct face to face talks included Levoyer who was called by the Peruvians the leader of the \"hard line\". While they ran, Levoyer staged exercises both to encourage his men and to undermine the morale of their Peruvian opponents who had to get used to the daily six o'clock in the morning start of the exercises, which included artillery and other displays of force.\n\n===Aftermath===\nBorder violence remained constant until the resolution of the [[History of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute#Resolution and arbitration|Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute]] in 1998 through the [[Brasilia Presidential Act]]. Violence occurred most of the time around January, which coincides with the month that the [[Rio Protocol]] was signed. Despite several proposals to complete demarcation of the border, no agreement was possible at that time.\n\nSeveral military bases were built up and down the Cordillera by both countries, and the region was militarized. The Peruvian bases were serviced by helicopter, while on the Ecuadorian side, gravel roads were constructed to several military border posts.\n\nSome sources claim that the Ecuadorian resistance to the full implementation of the border demarcation during the 1970s and 1980s was almost entirely due to domestic political struggles.\n\nAccording to the USIP, after this war, Ecuador's Foreign Ministry conducted a national opinion survey that reportedly confirmed the popularity of nullification of the Rio Protocol and Ecuador's right to sovereign access to the [[Amazon river]]. Thus, in 1983, the Ecuadorian congress reaffirmed its position on the nullity of the [[Rio Protocol]].\n\nIn the \"''Paquisha book, the whole truth''\" of the Ecuadorian writer Claudio Mena said the author argues that Ecuadorian President [[Jaime Rold\u00f3s Aguilera]] had planned to inaugurate on February 12 those surveillance posts that [[Ecuador]] had installed in the territory of [[Peru]] to show the world that this territory was \" Ecuadorian soil<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.is/IFXjg|title=Paquisha or the False Story|last=Mena Villamar|first=Claudio|work=Diary Hoy, Ecuador|access-date=}}</ref> \"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''[http://www.caretas.com.pe/1349/rio-cenepa/cenepa.html Interview with Peruvian President Fernando Belaunder Terry, Falso Paquisha Incident]'' Caretas\n*''[http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_164.shtml Detailed information about the military actions in the Paquisha Incident]''\n*''[http://ecuador.nativeweb.org/border/border1.html The 1995 Peruvian-Ecuadorian border conflict]\n\n{{Ecuador topics}}\n\n[[Category:Ecuadorian\u2013Peruvian wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:History of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:1981 in Peru]]\n[[Category:History of Peru]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Peru]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Ecuador\u2013Peru border]]\n[[Category:January 1981 events in South America]]\n[[Category:February 1981 events in South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Paquisha War\n| partof      = the [[History of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute|Ecuadorian-Peruvian conflicts]]\n| image       = Ecuador-Peru-Frontera.svg\n| image_size  = 280\n| caption     = Ecuador\u2013Peru border\n| date        = {{start and end dates|1981|01|22|1981|02|05|df=y}}\n| place       = Condor mountain range\n| result      = Peruvian Victory <ref>{{cite web|title=Conflicto del Alto Comaina, Ecured Cuba|url=https://www.ecured.cu/Conflicto_del_Alto_Comaina|accessdate=18 February 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018False Paquisha\u2019: 37 years after a military feat, Expreso Diary|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/actualidad/falso-paquisha-a-37-anos-de-una-proeza-militar/|accessdate=29 January 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The other victory: How we achieve peace with Ecuador|url=https://revistaideele.com/ideele/content/la-otra-victoria-c%C3%B3mo-logramos-la-paz-con-el-ecuador|accessdate=7 March 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Peru}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ecuador}}\n| commander1  = {{ubl|[[Fernando Bela\u00fande Terry]]|[[Rafael Hoyos Rubio]]}}\n| commander2  = [[Jaime Rold\u00f3s Aguilera]]\n| strength1   = unknown\n| strength2   = 53 men<ref>{{cite web|title=Paquisha, 35 a\u00f1os de este importante nombre en la historia del Ecuador|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/noticias/2016/01/21/nota/5359180/paquisha-nombre-historia-ecuador|accessdate=8 January 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| casualties1 = 17 killed\n| casualties2 = {{ubl|16 killed|30 wounded}}\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Ecuadorian-Peruvian}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Paquisha War''' ({{Lang-es|guerra de Paquisha}}) was a military clash that took place between January and February 1981 between [[Ecuador]] and [[Peru]] over the control of three watchposts. While Peru felt that the matter was already decided in the [[Ecuadorian-Peruvian War]] of 1941, Ecuador did not agree with the [[Rio de Janeiro Protocol]]. Later in 1998 the Guarantors of the Rio Protocol ruled that the border of the undelimited zone was indeed the line of the Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor, as Peru had been claiming since the 1940s. \n\nIn the aftermath of the incident, both sides increased their military presence along the [[Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor]] area and Cenepa Valley, starting an escalating spiral of tension and provocation that finally resulted in another military confrontation in 1995, the [[Cenepa War]].\n\nWhile the name ''Paquisha War'' is widely used by the international community and Ecuador, in Spanish this incident is also known as the '''Falso Paquisha War''' (''Conflicto del Falso Paquisha'') in Peru and, occasionally, as the '''Paquisha Incident''' or the '''Upper Comaina Conflict''' (''conflicto del Alto Comaina'').\n\n==Historical background==\n''For details on the history of the border dispute between Ecuador and Peru, please see [[History of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian territorial dispute]].''\n\n===The Paquisha or \"Fake Paquisha\" Incident===\nThe dispute revolved around the existence of three Ecuadorian military outposts, called Paquisha, Mayaico, and Machinaza, located in the valley of the Comaina River, beyond the eastern slopes of the [[Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor|Condor range]] (in Spanish, ''Cordillera del C\u00f3ndor''). While these posts were located in the as yet non-demarcated zone of the Ecuadorian-Peruvian border, the establishment of these posts was considered by the Peruvian Government as a violation of a ''[[status quo]]'' line arranged between the military leaders of both countries in the course of several meetings at the end of the 1970s. During these agreements both sides would have agreed not to establish any new military posts in the disputed areas,<ref>Mena, 1981</ref> which would have meant for Ecuador not to establish any military presence to the east of the ridgeline of the Condor Range.\n\nThe Ecuadorian possession of these posts was denounced by Peruvian representatives at the foreign ministers' meeting of the [[Organization of American States|OAS]], on February 2, 1981. During this meeting, the Peruvian Foreign Minister, [[Javier Arias Stella]], called the three Ecuadorian military outposts ''falsos'' (\"fakes\"), despite Ecuadorian sovereignty.\n\nEcuadorians indicated that these detachments corresponded to the \"Paquisha\" base established in Ecuadorian territory. But, after measuring the coordinates, it was found that they did not correspond to the aforementioned Paquisha accepted in the [[Rio Protocol|Protocol of Rio de Janeiro]] but, as the Peruvian president [[Fernando Bela\u00fande Terry|Fernando Bela\u00fande]] described it, to a \"False Paquisha\", a name he gave to distinguish it easily from the first Paquisha that was legal according to the Rio protocol of 1942<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/